      <div data-bk-layout="palm:9 hands:8 lap:7" class="rte">
        <p class="font-m">Responsive, viewport based, fonts should be restricted to use on headings and isolated blocks of text. Avoid using it on copy paragraphs and long blocks of text.

        <p>I would also advise against using medium or large sizes nearby normal (non-responsive) blocks of text because these viewport based texts can actually end up <em>smaller</em> at certain screen sizes.</p>

        <p>I've never been a fan of styling <code>h1, h2, h3</code>, etc directly or by tying their size and style to their heading number. What if h2 and h4 should visually look the same but not in every instance? Over time and with multiple maintainers the CSS and HTML end up tied in knots.</p>

        <p>The solution is simple; just define font styles to utility classes and apply where required regardless of the markup. If you want to style one list item to look like some hero text, go right ahead! It does not matter, the semantics are in your HTML markup and content.</p>
      </div>

